06100nam a22009255i 9781503610880DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20202019cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2019012268  a97815036108807 a10.1515/97815036108802doi  a(DE-B1597)563721  a(OCoLC)1122616706  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aBP65.B54bL5 2020 4aBP65.B54bL5 2020 7aSOC0480002bisacsh04a320.55/7223  aBE 22502rvk0(DE-625)rvk/10499:1 aLi, Darryl, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Universal Enemy :bJihad, Empire, and the Challenge of Solidarity /cDarryl Li. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (384 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStanford Studies in Middle Eastern and Islamic Societies and Cultures00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tTerms of Engagement -- tDramatis Personae -- tINTRODUCTION -- tPART I. JIHAD -- tChapter 1. MIGRATIONS -- tChapter 2. LOCATIONS -- tChapter 3. AUTHORITIES -- tChapter 4. GROUNDINGS -- tInterlude -- tEXCHANGING ARABS -- tPART II. OTHER UNIVERSALISMS -- tChapter 5. NON-ALIGNMENT -- tChapter 6. PEACEKEEPING -- tChapter 7. THE GLOBAL WAR ON TERROR -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aNo contemporary figure is more demonized than the Islamist foreign fighter who wages jihad around the world. Spreading violence, disregarding national borders, and rejecting secular norms, so-called jihadists seem opposed to universalism itself. In a radical departure from conventional wisdom on the topic, The Universal Enemy argues that transnational jihadists are engaged in their own form of universalism: these fighters struggle to realize an Islamist vision directed at all of humanity, transcending racial and cultural difference. Anthropologist and attorney Darryl Li reconceptualizes jihad as armed transnational solidarity under conditions of American empire, revisiting a pivotal moment after the Cold War when ethnic cleansing in the Balkans dominated global headlines. Muslim volunteers came from distant lands to fight in Bosnia-Herzegovina alongside their co-religionists, offering themselves as an alternative to the US-led international community. Li highlights the parallels and overlaps between transnational jihads and other universalisms such as the War on Terror, United Nations peacekeeping, and socialist Non-Alignment. Developed from more than a decade of research with former fighters in a half-dozen countries, The Universal Enemy explores the relationship between jihad and American empire to shed critical light on both.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aJihadxPolitical aspectszBosnia and Herzegovina. 0aMuslim soldierszBosnia and Herzegovina. 0aPanislamism. 0aSolidarityxReligious aspectsxIslam. 0aYugoslav War, 1991-1995xParticipation, Foreign. 0aYugoslav War, 1991-1995xParticipation, Muslim. 0aYugoslav War, 1991-1995zBosnia and Herzegovina. 70(DE-588)117546435X0(DE-627)10464336950(DE-576)516227777aDschihadismus2gnd 70(DE-588)4003725-30(DE-627)10638872X0(DE-576)20885262XaAusländer2gnd 70(DE-588)4027743-40(DE-627)1062834990(DE-576)20897220XaIslam2gnd 70(DE-588)4040921-10(DE-627)1062212050(DE-576)209042680aMuslim2gnd 70(DE-588)4055429-60(DE-627)1061582280(DE-576)209113790aSolidarität2gnd 70(DE-588)4164745-20(DE-627)1054451770(DE-576)209890576aKombattant2gnd 70(DE-588)4231763-00(DE-627)1049302090(DE-576)210358335aPanislamismus2gnd 70(DE-588)4288473-10(DE-627)1042815290(DE-576)210823194aIllegalität2gnd 70(DE-588)4305296-40(DE-627)1231872490(DE-576)21107599XaDjihad2gnd 70(DE-588)4460684-90(DE-627)2306121